<div id="review_89520401" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/89520401" />
    <a title="Ellis" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/287912-ellis"><img alt="Ellis" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1513280918p2/287912.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/89520401?book_show_action=true">Feb 13, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ellis" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ellis" href="/user/show/287912-ellis">Ellis</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/287912-ellis?shelf=apocalyptastic">apocalyptastic</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer89520401" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12518001239218267459">It&apos;s too bad this book is so poorly written, because the premise is pretty cool. The slipshod editing - you may think you&apos;re saying &quot;must of&quot; because that&apos;s what it sometimes sounds like, but you&apos;re actually saying &quot;must&apos;ve&quot; and any editor with an actual job should know this. The ridiculous characters - most of all, John, the hero who has it all. He&apos;s a professor, a doctor, a colonel, owns one of the only running cars left in America that the mayor <i>apologises for asking to borrow</i>, has a little b</span>
  <span id="freeText12518001239218267459" style="display:none">It's too bad this book is so poorly written, because the premise is pretty cool. The slipshod editing - you may think you're saying "must of" because that's what it sometimes sounds like, but you're actually saying "must've" and any editor with an actual job should know this. The ridiculous characters - most of all, John, the hero who has it all. He's a professor, a doctor, a colonel, owns one of the only running cars left in America that the mayor <i>apologises for asking to borrow</i>, has a little bit o' hippie in him, and is the only person who gets to talk for more than a sentence at a time. The preposterous outcomes - say what you like about lazy, dependent Americans, but I refuse to believe that a power outage, even on a national scale, would cause this kind of devastation in such a short amount of time. Fifteen thousand people in one town really would starve to death in less than two months? I'm sure there are people in the world who would love to get 1200 calories a day.<br /><br />At some point, the lady character who's there to be a sexual foil for our boy John tells him, "I feel like I'm in some bad novel." In my library copy someone wrote an asterisk next to this &amp; at the bottom of the page wrote "You are." <br /><br />Note: do not write in your library book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12518001239218267459" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


